{
  "answer": "**In the Yājñavalkya Smṛti (Chapter 1, verse 1.115 and its immediate context), there is no direct prescription regarding a wife's duties.**\n\nVerse 1.115 falls within the section on the duties of a householder (*gṛhasthadharmaprakaraṇam*, starting at verse 1.97). It instructs the householder (a twice-born man) to rise at the Brāhma Muḥūrta (roughly 4 a.m.) and reflect on his welfare, while not neglecting *dharma*, wealth (*artha*), and desire (*kāma*) at their proper times.[^1] The surrounding verses (e.g., 1.113–1.116) detail the householder's daily routine—escorting guests, evening worship, eating, honoring people by learning/age/wealth—and varṇa duties, but say nothing specific about wives.[^2]\n\nPrescriptions on a wife's duties (*strīdharmāḥ*) appear earlier, in the marriage section (*vivāhaprakaraṇam*, verses ~76–87):\n- Obeying her husband's word is her highest *dharma*; she must wait for a sinful husband until purified.[^3]\n- She should keep household utensils ordered, be skillful/cheerful/frugal/devoted to her husband, and salute her parents-in-law.[^4]\n- If her husband is away, she should avoid sports, adornment, gatherings, laughing, and visiting others.[^5]\n- Devoted to her husband's welfare, of good conduct, and sense-controlled, she gains fame and the highest afterlife.[^6]\n\n[^1]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.115, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-60edb7).\n[^2]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.113–1.116, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-d3a1d4-p-5fc775).\n[^3]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.77, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-c2ffdb).\n[^4]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.83, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-b3ed86).\n[^5]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.84, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-d35f05).\n[^6]: Yājñavalkya Smṛti 1.87, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-de5d3d).",
